rans-title=The theory of physical education and sportvan |accessdate= 28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nIon \u0218iclovan played four games at international level for [[Romania national football team|Romania]], including a 3\u20132 victory against [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]] at the [[1947 Balkan Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=19199|title=Ion \u0218iclovan |publisher=European Football|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=6458|title=Bulgaria - Romania 2:3|publisher=European Football|accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nHe wrote two volumes, both of them being about sport:<ref name=targul/><ref name=librarie/>\n* Teoria antrenamentului sportiv ''(The sports training theory)'' (1977)\n* Teoria educatiei fizice si sportului ''(The theory of physical education and sport)'' (1979)\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.labtof.ro/profil/ion-siclovan-1461/ Ion \u0218iclovan] at Labtof.ro\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:\u0218iclovan, Ion}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n[[Category:Romanian footballers]]\n[[Category:Romania international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Liga I players]]\n[[Category:Liga II players]]\n[[Category:Carmen Bucure\u015fti players]]\n[[Category:FC Dinamo Bucure\u0219ti players]]\n[[Category:Romanian writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian writers]]\n[[Category:Romanian male writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Romanian male writers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Arad, Romania]]\n", "name_user": "S.A. Julio", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ion_%C8%98iclovan"}
{"title_page": "Dulichius", "text_new": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = DulichiusProfile.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Dulichius\n| authority = [[Carl St\u00e5l|St\u00e5l]], 1866\n| display_parents = 3\n| synonyms = ''Formicoris'' Kirby, 1891\n}}\n\n'''''Dulichius'''''<ref>St\u00e5l C (1866[1865]) ''Hemiptera Africana'' 2:7, 89-90.</ref> is a genus of [[Hemiptera|bugs]] in the family [[Alydidae]] and [[Tribe (biology)|tribe]] [[Micrelytrini]].<ref name = CSF/>  It is notable for species which are [[ant mimic]]s.\n\n== Species ==\nThe ''Coreoidea Species File''<ref name = CSF>[http://coreoidea.speciesfile.org/Common/basic/Taxa.aspx?TaxonNameID=1186515 Coreoidea Species File: genus ''Dulichius'' St\u00e5l, 1866 (retrieved 20 April 2020)]</ref> lists:\n* ''[[Dulichius baptisti]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius concolor]]'' <small>Bergroth, 1912</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius cruszi]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius culani]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius gemellus]]'' <small>Haglund, 1895</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius inflatus]]'' <small>(Kirby, 1891)</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius katangensis]]'' <small>Schouteden, 1913</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius macrocephalus]]'' <small>Villiers, 1950</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius similis]]'' <small>Linnavuori, 1987</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius sinhaladvipa]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius tambapanni]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius tanamalwila]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius thompsoni]]'' <small>Distant, 1903</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius trispinosus]]'' <small>St\u00e5l, 1866</small> - '''type species'''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n{{taxonbar|from=Q21447629}}\n\n[[Category:Hemiptera of Asia]]\n[[Category:Alydidae]]\n[[Category:Hemiptera genera]]\n", "text_old": "{{Automatic taxobox\n| image = DulichiusProfile.jpg\n| image_caption = \n| taxon = Dulichius\n| authority = [[Carl St\u00e5l|St\u00e5l]], 1866\n| display_parents = 3\n| synonyms = ''Formicoris'' Kirby, 1891\n}}\n\n'''''Dulichius'''''<ref>St\u00e5l C (1866[1865]) ''Hemiptera Africana'' 2:7, 89-90.</ref> is a genus of [[Hemiptera|bugs]] in the family [[Alydidae]] and [[Tribe (biology)|tribe]] [[Micrelytrini]].<ref name = CSF/>  It is notable for species which are [[ant mimic]]s.\n\n== Species ==\nThe ''Coreoidea Species File''<ref name = CSF>[http://coreoidea.speciesfile.org/Common/basic/Taxa.aspx?TaxonNameID=1186515 Coreoidea Species File: genus ''Dulichius'' St\u00e5l, 1866 (retrieved 20 April 2020)]</ref> lists:\n* ''[[Dulichius baptisti]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius concolor]]'' <small>Bergroth, 1912</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius cruszi]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius culani]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius gemellus]]'' <small>Haglund, 1895</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius inflatus]]'' <small>(Kirby, 1891)</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius katangensis]]'' <small>Schouteden, 1913</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius macrocephalus]]'' <small>Villiers, 1950</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius similis]]'' <small>Linnavuori, 1987</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius sinhaladvipa]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius tambapanni]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius tanamalwila]]'' <small>Fernando, 1957</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius thompsoni]]'' <small>Distant, 1903</small>\n* ''[[Dulichius trispinosus]]'' <small>St\u00e5l, 1866</small> - '''type species'''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n*{{commonscat inline}}\n{{taxonbar|from=Q21447629}}\n\n[[Category:Hemiptera of Asia]]\n[[Category:Alydidae]]\n[[Category:Hemiptera genera]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:replaced: Links \u2192 links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dulichius"}
{"title_page": "RugbyWA", "text_new": "{{No footnotes|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox sport governing body\n|name             = Western Australia Rugby Union\n|abbrev           = RugbyWA\n|logo             = \n|logosize         = 150px\n|sport            = [[Rugby union]]\n|category         = \n|image            = \n|caption          = \n|jurisdiction     = [[Western Australia]]\n|founded          = {{start date and age|df=y|1893||}}\n|aff              = \n|affdate          = \n|region           = \n|regionyear       = \n|headquarters     = \n|location         = \n|president        = \n|chairman         = \n|chairperson      = \n|chair            = \n|chiefexec        = \n|vicepresident    = \n|director         = \n|secretary        = \n|coach            = \n|womenscoach      = \n|key staff        = \n|operating income = \n|sponsor          = \n|year closed      = \n|replaced         = \n|prevfounded      = \n|url              = https://wa.rugby/\n|countryflag      = \n|countryflag2     = \n|countryflag3     = \n|more             = \n|membership       = }}\n\nThe '''Western Australia Rugby Union (RugbyWA)''' is the [[Sports governing body|governing body]] of [[rugby union]] in [[Western Australia]], it was founded in 1893 and the inaugural 4 team competition commenced in 1895 with the I Zingari, Fremantle, Swans and Midland Junction Club's taking part. The WARU Senior Grade competition was contested from 1895 to 1913.\n\nThe Rugby Football code went into recess in the west from the 1914 season until 1928 when 4 Clubs; Wanderers, Rangers, Wallabies and Fremantle revived the First Grade Club Competition.\n\nIn 2004, RugbyWA successfully secured the fourth Australian Super 12 licence, entering a team in the expanded [[Super Rugby|Super 14]] competition from 2006, called the [[Western Force]]. RugbyWA has also established a series of development programs. The development team is the Perth Spirit, which has competed in the [[Australian Rugby Championship]] in 2007 and the [[National Rugby Championship]] since 2014.\n\nThere are currently 10 RugbyWA Board Members, President, D G Redpath who was re-elected in March 2012. Dr R J Perry is the current Chairman and Mr Arthur Hill is the current Patron.\n\nThe RugbyWA is a not-for-profit organisation run by its shareholding organisations \u2013 WA clubs and affiliated bodies (juniors, schools, referees, women's and country rugby). RugbyWA incorporates both Professional and Community Rugby. There is no private ownership of RugbyWA with profit generated re-invested into the game at all levels in Western Australia.\n\n=={{anchor|premier}}Premier Grade==\n\n{{Infobox rugby league cup\n| title          = Fortescue Premier Grade\n| current_season = <!--leave blank-->\n| logo           = \n| logo_caption   = Fortescue Premier Grade Logo\n| pixels         = 300px\n| caption        = \n| sport          = [[Rugby union]]\n| founded        = {{start date and age|df=y|1928||}}\n| inaugural      = \n| folded         = \n| teams          = 14\n| country        = {{flagcountry|Western Australia}}\n| champion       = Cottesloe\n| season         = 2019\n| most_champs    = [[File:600px Giallo e Blu orizzontale con striscia bianca.png|20px|border]] [[Nedlands Rugby Union Football Club|Nedlands]] <small>(15 titles)</small>\n| website        = https://wa.rugby/competitions/comp?id=2GY4X4DfagBFcN3oz\n| ceo            = \n| TV             = \n| related_comps  = \n}}\n{{Main|Western Australia Premier Rugby}}\nThe Premier Grade is the highest level of [[Western Australia]] domestic club rugby union competition, contested annually from early April to mid August. It is managed by the [[Western Australia Rugby Union]] (RugbyWA), the FMG Premier Grade was named for lead sponsor Fortescue Metals.\n\n=== Premiers (since 1963) ===\n{{col-float|firstcol=16em}}\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! style=\"padding:0 2.5em\"|Champion\n|-\n|2019\n|[[File:600px Azzurro e Blu con striscia ce